==English==
===Etymology===
From Middle English ''vain'' < Old French ''vain'' < Latin ''[[vanus|vānus]]'', "empty"

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/veɪn/}}
*{{AHD|/vān/}}
*{{audio|en-us-vain.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-eɪn|-eɪn]]

===Adjective===
'''vain'''
#overly proud of oneself, especially when concerning appearance
#:''Every writer is a narcissist. This does not mean that he is vain; it only means that he is hopelessly self-absorbed.'' &ndash;Leo Rosten
#having very little [[substance]]
#pointless, [[futile]]
#:''It is vain to do with more what can be done with fewer.'' &ndash;William of Occam

